.SH NAME
.PP
Browse \[en] Open a file or an URL in a browser
.SH SYNOPSIS
.PP
\f[B]browse\f[R] [\f[I]options\f[R]] [\f[I]url\f[R]]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.PP
Open a file or an URL in a \f[C]$BROWSER\f[R].
To use the program, the \f[C]$BROWSER\f[R] environment variable must be
set in your profile, and point to a valid browser program.
Good options might be \f[C]open\f[R], or a specific web browser:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
export BROWSER=\[dq]open\[dq]
export BROWSER=\[dq]firefox --new-tab\[dq]
export BROWSER=\[dq]google-chrome\[dq]
\f[R]
.fi
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.B \f[C]-h\f[R], \f[C]--help\f[R]
Print help.
.TP
.B \f[C]-v\f[R], \f[C]--version\f[R]
Print version number.
.TP
.B \f[I]url\f[R]
Resource to open.
.IP \[bu] 2
If \f[C]-\f[R], the URL is read from \f[C]STDIN\f[R].
.IP \[bu] 2
If \f[C]?\f[R], the URL is prompted for.
.IP \[bu] 2
If omitted, opens the current working directory.
.IP \[bu] 2
If starts with \f[C].\f[R] or \f[C]/\f[R], is resolved as a local
\f[C]file\f[R].
.IP \[bu] 2
If scheme is omitted, \f[C]https\f[R] is used.
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.TP
.B \f[C]BROWSER\f[R]
Sets the used browser program.
.TP
.B \f[C]PWD\f[R]
Used for resolving local URLs relative to the current working directory.
.SH FILES
.PP
Depends on external programs \f[C]bash\f[R], \f[C]cat\f[R],
\f[C]dirname\f[R] and \f[C]realpath\f[R].
.SH EXAMPLES
.PP
Open an URL:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
$ browse https://example.com
$ browse example.com
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Open the \f[C]example\f[R] directory:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
$ cd path/to/example && browse
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Open a local \f[C]file.html\f[R]:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
$ browse ./file.html
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
From stdin:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
$ echo \[dq]https://example.com\[dq] | browse -
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
Prompt for an URL:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
$ browse ?
? URL:
\f[R]
.fi
